<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1260,2005]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">
<bibRefCitation author="Bleeker, P." box="[151,320,1260,1285]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" pagination="65 - 74" refId="ref1544" refString="Bleeker, P. (1849) A contribution to the knowledge of the ichthyological fauna of Celebes. Journal of the Indian Archipelago and Eastern Asia (Singapore), 3 (1), 65 - 74." type="journal article" year="1849">Bleeker (1849)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1849" box="[442,588,1260,1284]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogonoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[442,588,1260,1284]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Apogonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid genus from southwestern 
<collectingRegion box="[998,1102,1260,1285]" country="Indonesia" name="Sulawesi Utara" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Sulawesi</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1114,1227,1260,1285]" name="Indonesia" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
. However, no 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,1261,1285]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">type</typeStatus>
is known and the genus has only been identified as belonging to an unknown species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1181,1321,1295,1320]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Apogonidae</taxonomicName>
. All three species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Randall &amp; Smith" authorityYear="1988" box="[270,380,1332,1355]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[270,380,1332,1355]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Cercamia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
agree with Bleeker’s description (dorsal fin VI-I,9; anal fin II,11; pectoral fin 11; no teeth on the palatines and on the vomer, villiform teeth on dentary and premaxilla; and slender body). We assume the lack of a spine or serrations on the “gill cover” by Bleeker may be the fact that the 1–3 spines on the preopercle are very tiny. Bleeker likely overlooked the anteriormost branchiostegal ray. The probability of finding the lost 
<typeStatus box="[1305,1353,1440,1464]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">type</typeStatus>
is very low given the known facts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1260,2005]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">
Prevailing usage must be maintained for 
<taxonomicName authority="Randall &amp; Smith 1988" authorityName="Randall &amp; Smith" authorityYear="1988" box="[665,1039,1511,1536]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[665,774,1512,1535]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Cercamia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Randall, J. E. &amp; Smith, C. L." box="[782,1039,1511,1536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" pagination="1 - 9" refId="ref1844" refString="Randall, J. E. &amp; Smith, C. L. (1988) Two new species and a new genus of cardinalfishes (Perciformes: Apogonidae) from Rapa, South Pacific Ocean. American Museum Novitates, 2926, 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="1988">Randall &amp; Smith 1988</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(Article 23.9) if its two conditions are both met. Article 23.9.1.1 of the Code (International Code of 
<bibRefCitation author="International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature" box="[905,1268,1548,1573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" refId="ref1737" refString="International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature (1999) International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London, Fourth edition, online http: // www. nhm. ac. uk / hosted-sites / iczn / code /, (accessed September 2018)" type="url" year="1999">Zoological Nomenclature, 1999</bibRefCitation>
) has been met because 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1849" box="[246,392,1584,1608]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogonoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[246,392,1584,1608]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Apogonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been used after 1899 as a senior synonym or homonym. Article 23.9.1.2 has been met because 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Randall &amp; Smith" authorityYear="1988" box="[249,359,1620,1643]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[249,359,1620,1643]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Cercamia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym or homonym has been used for a particular taxon as its presumed valid name in at least 25 works published by at least 10 authors in the immediately preceding 50 years (see 
<tableCitation box="[1312,1395,1655,1680]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,152,175]" captionText="TABLE 1. Literature that refer to Cercamia, C. cladara, C. eremia, and C. melanogaster beginning with the 1988 establishment of the genus Cercamia through 2004." pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Table 1</tableCitation>
for 
<date box="[151,277,1692,1716]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" value="1988" valueMax="2004">1988–2004</date>
usage in 32 publications) and encompassing a span of not less than 10 years (see 
<tableCitation box="[1208,1292,1692,1717]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,235,347,369]" captionText="TABLE 2. Literature that refer to Cercamia, C. cladara, C. eremia, and C. melanogaster in a 12 year span 2005 through 2017." pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Table 2</tableCitation>
for 13 years from 
<date box="[213,364,1727,1752]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" value="2005" valueMax="2017">2005 to 2017</date>
usage in 25 publications and more than 10 authors). Based on the evidence presented here we declare that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Randall &amp; Smith" authorityYear="1988" box="[287,396,1764,1787]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[287,396,1764,1787]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Cercamia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the valid younger generic name (
<emphasis box="[796,989,1765,1788]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">nomen protectum</emphasis>
) while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1849" box="[1075,1221,1764,1788]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogonoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1075,1221,1764,1788]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Apogonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the invalid older name (
<emphasis box="[228,394,1800,1824]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">nomen oblitum</emphasis>
) following Article 23.9.2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1260,2005]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,356]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="581" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">
Geographic evidence from the literature cited in the 
<tableCitation box="[814,911,1836,1861]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,152,175]" captionText="TABLE 1. Literature that refer to Cercamia, C. cladara, C. eremia, and C. melanogaster beginning with the 1988 establishment of the genus Cercamia through 2004." pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Tables 1</tableCitation>
and 
<tableCitation box="[972,986,1836,1860]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,235,347,369]" captionText="TABLE 2. Literature that refer to Cercamia, C. cladara, C. eremia, and C. melanogaster in a 12 year span 2005 through 2017." pageId="1" pageNumber="580">2</tableCitation>
leads to the conclusion that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Randall &amp; Smith" authorityYear="1988" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cladara">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Cercamia cladara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not conspecific with 
<taxonomicName box="[518,689,1872,1895]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogonoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macassariensis">
<emphasis box="[518,689,1872,1895]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">macassariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Bleeker never obtained any fishes or described any fishes from Polynesia (Weber &amp; de 
<bibRefCitation author="Weber, M. &amp; de Beaufort, F. L." box="[417,582,1908,1933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" refId="ref2021" refString="Weber, M. &amp; de Beaufort, F. L. (1964 edition) The fishes of the Indo-Australian Archipelago. 1: Index of the Ichthyological Papers of P. Bleeker. Brill, E. J. Ltd, Leiden, 440 pp." type="book" year="1964">Beaufort 1964</bibRefCitation>
). Bleeker’s description is no help in deciding if he had a specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[1359,1436,1909,1932]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eremia">
<emphasis box="[1359,1436,1909,1932]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">eremia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(widespread), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Allen, Erdmann &amp; Mahardini" authorityYear="2015" box="[312,464,1944,1968]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melanogaster">
<emphasis box="[312,464,1944,1968]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">melanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(known only from the eastern side of New 
<collectingCountry box="[958,1041,1943,1968]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Guinea</collectingCountry>
) as the younger species name. The known station locations in the literature (
<tableCitation box="[664,759,1980,2005]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,235,347,369]" captionText="TABLE 2. Literature that refer to Cercamia, C. cladara, C. eremia, and C. melanogaster in a 12 year span 2005 through 2017." pageId="1" pageNumber="580">Table 2</tableCitation>
) for the younger synonym 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[1109,1186,1981,2004]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="580" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eremia">
<emphasis box="[1109,1186,1981,2004]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="580">eremia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
supports identifying 
<taxonomicName box="[151,322,152,175]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogonoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macassariensis">
<emphasis box="[151,322,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">macassariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the senior synonym. Article 23.9.1.2 is met for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[901,978,152,175]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eremia">
<emphasis box="[901,978,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">eremia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the junior synonym or homonym has been used for a particular taxon, as its presumed valid name, in at least 25 publications (57 cited publications, the majority using 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[320,396,224,247]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eremia">
<emphasis box="[320,396,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">eremia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), published by at least 10 authors in the immediately preceding 50 years and encompassing a span of not less than 10 years. Based on the evidence presented here we declare that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[1124,1201,261,284]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Cercamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eremia">
<emphasis box="[1124,1201,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">eremia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the valid younger species name (
<emphasis box="[315,509,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">nomen protectum</emphasis>
) while 
<taxonomicName box="[592,763,296,319]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Apogonoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macassariensis">
<emphasis box="[592,763,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">macassariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the invalid older name (
<emphasis box="[1060,1226,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">nomen oblitum</emphasis>
) following Article 23.9.2.
</paragraph>
